\f1\b\fs40 \cf2 Chapter 4
\f0\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf2 Fox Was Wrong (Sort Of)
\f0\b0 \
\

\fs28 Vera came back without the beavers.\
\
She did not say anything at first. She just stood at the river\'92s edge and looked at it.\
\
Sage and Pip looked at her.\
\
\'93There\'92s a fallen tree,\'94 said Sage. \'93At the river bend. Blocking the channel. That\'92s why it\'92s rising.\'94\
\
Vera was quiet for a moment.\
\
\'93I knew it was flooding,\'94 she said finally.\
\
\'93You did,\'94 said Sage.\
\
\'93I just didn\'92t know why.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 said Sage. \'93You didn\'92t ask.\'94\
\
Vera\'92s ears went back slightly.\
\
Just slightly.\
\
\'93\'85I should have asked,\'94 she said.\
\
Pip patted her on the shoulder. \'93You got us the beavers though! That\'92s still good.\'94\
\
\'93The beavers said they can\'92t help yet.\'94\
\
\'93Oh.\'94 Pip thought about this. \'93Well. You got us 
\f2\i to
\f0\i0  the beavers. That counts.\'94\
\
Vera looked at him.\
\
Pip smiled his enormous Pip smile.\
\
Vera sighed. But her ears came back up.\
\page \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs40 \cf2 Chapter 5
\f0\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf2 Night Work
\f0\b0 \
\

\fs28 By the time the sun went down, the burrows were knee-deep in water.\
\
The bunnies had already begun.\
\
They moved fast and quiet through their underground tunnels, guiding mouse families out one by one. No panic. No pushing. Just small paws and calm voices and knowing exactly where to go.\
\
\'93This way, please.\'94\
\
\'93Mind your step.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re safe now.\'94\
\
Above ground, Vera watched and thought.\
\

\f2\i Beavers can\'92t move the tree. Not tonight. But the water needs somewhere to go.
\f0\i0 \
\
She looked at the Mapleaf.\
\
Its veins were still dark \'97 but one branch pointed slightly left. Toward the mossy clearing.\
\

\f2\i A redirect
\f0\i0 , she thought. 
\f2\i Not a fix. Just enough.
\f0\i0 \
\
\'93Pip,\'94 she said. \'93I need you to get everyone who can sing.\'94\
\
Pip\'92s eyes went wide. \'93Everyone?\'94\
\
\'93Everyone.\'94\
\
Pip was already gone before she finished the sentence.\
\page \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs40 \cf2 Chapter 6
\f0\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf2 Singing to the Mud
\f0\b0 \
\

\fs28 They gathered at the river\'92s edge.\
\
Vera. Pip. Sage. Bram and two other beavers. A family of deer. Three raccoons. The otter from the slide, who had been asked twice and complained once and showed up anyway.\
\
Sage stood at the back.\
\
There were a lot of creatures. A lot of sounds. A lot of movement.\
\
She took a slow breath.\
\

\f2\i It\'92s okay
\f0\i0 , she thought. 
\f2\i I know what my part is.
\f0\i0 \
\
Vera stood at the front.\
\
\'93We\'92re going to redirect the water,\'94 she said. \'93Just to the mossy clearing. Just for tonight. The beavers will fix the tree tomorrow when it\'92s safe.\'94\
\
Bram nodded. \'93We\'92ll be there at first light.\'94\
\
\'93We sing to the mud on my count,\'94 said Vera. \'93Low and slow. Like this\'97\'94\
\
She hummed a single note.\
\
The deer picked it up. Then the raccoons. Then Pip, loudly and slightly off-key but with great enthusiasm.\
\
The mud at the river\'92s edge began to shift.\
\
Slowly at first. Then more.\
\
A small channel opened, curving left toward the clearing.\
\
The water followed.\
\
It was not elegant. It was not permanent.\
\
But the river slowed.\
\
And the burrows held.\
\page \pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs40 \cf2 Chapter 7
\f0\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf2 Good Morning
\f0\b0 \
\

\fs28 By midnight, the mouse families were safe in temporary nests above ground.\
\
The bunnies had done their job perfectly. The mud had done its job well enough. The beavers would do their job in the morning.\
\
When morning came, they did.\
\
Bram and three other beavers arrived at the river bend at first light. The fallen tree \'97 a great old oak, broken at the root \'97 lay heavy across the channel.\
\
It took four beavers and two hours.\
\
But they moved it.\
\
The water rushed through the cleared channel with a sound like relief. The singing mud, no longer needed, settled quietly back into the riverbank. The redirect was gone as if it had never been.\
\
By the time the sun was fully up, the burrows were draining.\
\
By the time the birds began to sing, everything was back the way it should be.\
\
Vera sat on a rock by the river, watching the water run clear and calm.\
\
Pip flopped down next to her. He had mud on his nose and a glow mushroom in each paw that he was using as tiny lanterns, even though it was now broad daylight.\
\
Sage settled beside them both, slowly, the way Sage did everything.\
\
\'93We fixed it,\'94 said Pip.\
\
\'93We fixed it,\'94 said Vera. \'93Properly.\'94\
\
Sage was quiet for a moment. She was looking back toward the river bend.\
\
\'93The tree,\'94 she said. \'93Did it fall on its own?\'94\
\
Bram, still at the water\'92s edge, turned back toward them.\
\
\'93Hard to say,\'94 he said slowly. \'93The roots let go. But the damage to those roots was old. Very old.\'94 He shook his head. \'93I\'92ll remember it.\'94\
\
Sage nodded slowly. She filed it away.\
\
\'93Next time,\'94 said Vera quietly, \'93I\'92ll ask why first.\'94\
\
Pip looked at her.\
\
\'93You say that every time something goes wrong,\'94 he said cheerfully.\
\
Vera stared at him.\
\
\'93This is the first time something has gone wrong.\'94\
\
\'93I know,\'94 said Pip. \'93But I have a feeling it won\'92t be the last.\'94\
\
He held up both glowing mushrooms like tiny torches and marched off down the path toward home.\
\
Vera and Sage looked at each other.\
\
Then they followed him.\
\
Because in Whisperwood, that was usually the right thing to do.\
